text=Congrats on building the DS! I built one on Ceti for the hell of it,%0atoo. It took me six months to research and build up the bases once I'd%0adecided to build it. It never got out of its native region. There was a%0aplayer who had a woefully underdefended base. I marched the DS over%0athere and crunched it. I then went to a Heiho base (Heiho being the%0abaddest guild at the time) that had pring-4 and hit it. I then quit the%0agame. I was later told I set off the server war. Even if I didn't it was%0astill fun.%0a%0a(:*toc:)%0a%0aI chose to put this on my wiki rather than a specific message. This%0ashoudl discuss my understanding of the issues surrounding a Death Star.%0a%0aKilling a Death Star%0a====================%0a%0aTechnically, any unit can kill a DS. You know that a unit that can't%0apass through the shields still transfers 1 percent of its power. So, a%0aFighter transfers .04 power; 100 FTs pass through 4 power. So, multiply%0ayour DS' Armour by four (or five for a high-laser tech), and that's how%0amany FTs you'll need. FTs, in ahigh enough number, are always the most%0aefficient killer. Any unit with power less than your shield should be%0atreated the same. Cruisers and HCs are shield raped units to your DS, my%0aCruiser will still deliver 5 points of damage per CR; an HC would%0adeliver 10.%0a%0aBattleships are preferable because of their high efficiency and low%0anumbers, along with Ion Frigates in higher numbers. Think anything with%0aIon. The Ion Bombers and Ion Frigates have 1/2 of their power pass%0athrough. Battleships do not, but they are still ion-based. Look at your%0aIB and IF, divided their power by two. Divide your DS armour by that%0avalue. That's how many IBs or IFs are required to kill. IFs tend to be%0amore efficient, so I bet their numbers will be better.%0a%0a>>formula%3c%3c%0a%0aThe formula for attacking a unit with higher armour than the attacker's power:%0a%0aArmour / (Power - Shield) = number of attackers%0a%0aFormula for attacking a unit with lower armour than the attacker's power:%0a%0a(Armour + Shield) / Power = number of defenders killed.%0a%0aFor "shield raped" units:%0a%0aArmour / Power * 100 = number of attackers required.%0a%0aRemember to multiply base defenses accordingly.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aUsing a Death Star%0a==================%0a%0aWhat to use the DS for? It's been called a credit piggy bank; or a%0apiata. My [[new fighter rule analysis]] shows the armour cost%0aefficiency. DS has a .11 efficiency; which means only two ships are%0aworse in armour cost efficiency. That is units with a higher value are%0amore efficient when the derbs are harvested. So, the utility is limited.%0a%0a>>note%3c%3c%0aKnow what it takes to kill a DS by unit type. Run the numbers and keep%0anote of them. Likewise, know what your Death Star can kill; and keep a%0anote.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aTreat a DS like a Leviathan short-stack: good for crunching%0afleets with units less than BB in size; or with an insufficient number%0aof BBs. If we could catch a fleet in a retreat trap, then you could%0acrunch it. As long as the fleet does not have the numbers to kill the%0aDS, you' can crunch it down.%0a%0aYou'll want to keep credits on hand to pay for repairing the DS, which%0ais half its construction cost. You never know when your DS will be%0aholding on with only 1 percent left and need to be repaired.%0a%0aTry not to use Death Stars in the attack against a pring-defended base,%0aespecially multiple prings. The Death Star's real strength is its%0ashielding.%0a%0aProtecting a Death Star%0a=======================%0a%0aHow to protect the DS? There are two ways: defense-in-depth and strength-in-numbers.%0a%0aDefense in Depth%0a----------------%0a%0aConsider modern naval warfare. The Carrier is the%0aqueen of the fleet. How do navies protect them? Cruisers, Submarines,%0aDestroyers and Fighters; defense-in-depth. You will likewise want a%0asupport fleet capable of defending your DS. What does this mean?%0a%0a'''Build a support fleet that is efficient against BBs.''' You already%0aknow what units are efficient against your Death Star. Build a support%0afleet efficient against that threat.%0a%0aFirst, build enough Cruisers to kill all the BBs required to kill the%0aDS. Cruisers are efficient against BBs, so use this to your advantage.%0aThis requires you know how many BBs are required, then make sure you%0ahave enough. Battleship efficiency assumes not all BBs are killed;%0ahaving enough Cruisers to kill them tips the scale back toward the Death%0aStar%0a%0aSecond, remember that the Cruisers now need to be defended, and defend%0athe accordingly. Remember that Cruisers are vulnerable to Destroyers,%0aCorvettes, Frigates, Heavy Bombers and Fighers. These are all meat%0a(unshielded), which means they are all vulnerable to Fighters. So,%0ayou'll want enough fighters to kill what an attacker might bring to kill%0ayour Cruisers.  Calculate which of these units is most efficient against%0ayour Cruisers, and then calculate the Fighters necessary. The Death Star%0ais at least nice enough to carry many of the FTs you'll need.%0a%0aSo, your Death Star Support Fleet would include: Cruisers and Fighters;%0athe quintessence of the [[Small Fleet Doctrine]]. Think of this as either defense-in-depth or Small Fleet defense.%0a%0aWhile the Death Star conveys a bonus to your fleet, it might be safer to%0anot consider that bonus when calculating your defense fleet.%0a%0aCapital Strength in Numbers%0a---------------------------%0a%0aThe second approach is to create a Stack, which provides strength in numbers.%0aSimply put, create a stack of a capital unit: Titans, Levis, Dreads or Death%0aStars. Yes, these are vulnerable to Battleships (or Heavy Cruisers) as%0aappropriate. But, their large numbers make it more difficult to bring enough of%0aan attacking fleet to bear.%0a%0aHarvest the Derbs%0a-----------------%0a%0aFinally, have enough Recyclers ''nearby'' to harvest ''all'' the derbs.  Keep%0athe Recyclers away from your fleet as they provide no value in defense but%0abenefit your attacker.  Assume your DS and its support fleet is destroyed. You%0awill want _at least_ one Recycler for every twenty credits of your fleet's value.%0aThis will allow harvesting all of your fleet in one tick. Ideally, you'd%0awant one RC per ten credits, which allows you to harvest both your fleet%0aand the attackers. This reduces the vulnerability of your RC fleet by%0anot requiring that they loiter over the derbs.%0a%0aAs a point of reference, you need around 23,000 RCs to harvest your%0aDeath Star's derbs alone. So, you'd want around 45,000 RCs to harvest%0ayour DS and the attacker's derbs.%0a%0a(:comment This page has been edited using Pywe:)
